statement:
Let

\begin{align*}A = \begin{bmatrix}
1 & 3 \\ 3 & 8
\end{bmatrix}
\qquad 
B = \begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0 & -1 \\ -3 & 1 & 0
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

Calculate the following whenever defined. Otherwise state
\textbf{undefined} and include a brief explanation.

A matrix $D$ such that $DB = I_{3}$ where $I_{3}$ is the $3 \times 3$
identity matrix.

sols:
We proceed as in the hint. Let

$D = \begin{bmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \\ e & f \end{bmatrix}$

Then we have

\begin{align*}
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix}
= DB &= \begin{bmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \\ e & f \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0 & -1 \\ -3 & 1 & 0
\end{bmatrix}\\
&=  \begin{bmatrix} (a)(1) + (b)(-3) & (a)(0)+(b)(1) & (a)(-1) + (b)(0)\\ 
(c)(1) + (d)(-3) & (c)(0)+(d)(1) & (c)(-1) + (d)(0)\\  
(e)(1) + (f)(-3) & (e)(0)+(f)(1) & (e)(-1) + (f)(0) \end{bmatrix}\\
&= \begin{bmatrix} a-3b & b & -a\\ c-3d & d & -c \\ e-3f & f & -e \end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

Looking at the first row on the matrices on the left and right gives

\begin{align*}
a - 3b &= 1\\
b &= 0 \\
-a &= 0 \end{align*}

and this is inconsistent since the last two imply that both \emph{a} and
\emph{b} are zero and this contradicts the first line. Thus no such
matrix D exists.
